{
  "texts": [
    "Incorporating such insights into AI models enhances their biological plausibility and accuracy in predicting multisensory outcomes.",
    "These models support applications like flavor pairing, where the combined effects of smell and taste are evaluated computationally to improve culinary creativity or product design.",
    "Ultimately, the intersection of olfactory and gustatory research through AI not only deepens our scientific understanding of sensory processing but also drives innovation across product development, personalization, and sensory evaluation.",
    "Aspect Olfactory domain Gustatory domain Data Challenges -Sensor drift and cross-sensitivity -Lack of standardized odor descriptors -Sparse labeled datasets -Subjective taste variability -Limited labeled data for complex mixtures -Class imbalance in tastant datasets AI Applications -Odor classification and mapping -Molecular structure-toscent prediction -Multimodal integration with EEG/e-nose -Taste attribute prediction -Compound-receptor modeling -Ingredient optimization and flavor design Industrial Use Cases -Fragrance formulation -Disease detection via breath analysis -Food spoilage detection -Personalized nutrition -Smart recipe generation -Sensory evaluation in product development Table 5 Comparative overview of data challenges, AI applications, and industrial use cases in olfactory and gustatory research Approach Representative models Model-specific features Common strengths Common weaknesses Multimodal Transformers (Xu et al. 2023) Models long-range dependencies across sensory and non-sensory inputs (e.g., smell, text, image) Table 4 (continued) 1 3",
    "Despite the numerous similarities in AI applications, the fundamental differences in sensory processing between olfaction and gustation significantly shape consumer experiences and product development strategies."
  ]
}